Gerard Manley Hopkins (1844&#150;89).  Poems.  1918.
 
31.  Spring and Fall
   to a young child
 









 
M&Aacute;RGAR&Eacute;T, &aacute;re you gr&iacute;eving
Over Goldengrove unleaving?
Le&aacute;ves, l&iacute;ke the things of man, you
With your fresh thoughts care for, can you?
&Aacute;h! &aacute;s the heart grows older        5
It will come to such sights colder
By and by, nor spare a sigh
Though worlds of wanwood leafmeal lie;
And yet you w&iacute;ll weep and know why.
Now no matter, child, the name:        10
S&oacute;rrow's spr&iacute;ngs &aacute;re the same.
Nor mouth had, no nor mind, expressed
What heart heard of, ghost guessed:
It &iacute;s the blight man was born for,
It is Margaret you mourn for.        15


 See Notes.

 











