Verse &gt; Gerard Manley Hopkins &gt; Poems




  PREVIOUS

NEXT  

 
CONTENTS &#183; BIBLIOGRAPHIC RECORD







Gerard Manley Hopkins (1844&#150;89).  Poems.  1918.
 
34.  &#145;As kingfishers catch fire, dragonflies dr&aacute;w fl&aacute;me'
  









 
AS kingfishers catch fire, dragonflies dr&aacute;w fl&aacute;me;
As tumbled over rim in roundy wells
Stones ring; like each tucked string tells, each hung bell's
Bow swung finds tongue to fling out broad its name;
Each mortal thing does one thing and the same:        5
Deals out that being indoors each one dwells;
Selves&#151;goes itself; myself it speaks and spells,
Crying Wh&aacute;t I do is me: for that I came.
 

&Iacute; say m&oacute;re: the just man justices;
K&eacute;eps gr&aacute;ce: th&aacute;t keeps all his goings graces;        10
Acts in God's eye what in God's eye he is&#151;
Chr&iacute;st&#151;for Christ plays in ten thousand places,
Lovely in limbs, and lovely in eyes not his
To the Father through the features of men's faces.


 See Notes.

 











