CONTENTS &#183; BIBLIOGRAPHIC RECORD







Gerard Manley Hopkins (1844&#150;89).  Poems.  1918.
 
39.  (The Soldier)
  









 
YES. Why do we &aacute;ll, seeing of a soldier, bless him? bless
Our redcoats, our tars? Both these being, the greater part,
But frail clay, nay but foul clay. Here it is: the heart,
Since, proud, it calls the calling manly, gives a guess
That, hopes that, makesbelieve, the men must be no less;        5
It fancies, feigns, deems, dears the artist after his art;
And fain will find as sterling all as all is smart,
And scarlet wear the spirit of w&aacute;r th&eacute;re express.
 

Mark Christ our King. He knows war, served this soldiering through;
He of all can handle a rope best. There he bides in bliss        10
Now, and s&eacute;eing somewh&eacute;re some m&aacute;n do all that man can do,
For love he leans forth, needs his neck must fall on, kiss,
And cry &#145;O Christ-done deed! So God-made-flesh does too:
Were I come o'er again' cries Christ &#145;it should be this'.


 See Notes.

 











